00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:35,095
God!

238
00:17:35,896 --> 00:17:37,180
I don't belong here!

239
00:17:37,181 --> 00:17:38,681
<font color=#FF551>MAN:</font> We have a winner!

240
00:17:38,682 --> 00:17:40,516
<font color=#FF551>FAT ASS:</font> I wanna go home!

241
00:17:40,517 --> 00:17:42,435
And it's Fat Ass by a nose!

242
00:17:42,436 --> 00:17:45,688
Hey, it's the fat guy! It's the fat guy!

243
00:17:45,689 --> 00:17:49,609
Fresh fish! Fresh fish! Fresh fish!

244
00:17:49,610 --> 00:17:52,403
<font color=#FF551>FAT ASS:</font> I don't belong here!

245
00:17:52,404 --> 00:17:53,696
<font color=#FF551>ALL:</font>  Fresh fish!

246
00:17:53,697 --> 00:17:57,616
I wanna go home. I want my mommy.

247
00:17:58,117 --> 00:18:00,453
<font color=#FF551>MAN:</font> I had your mother.
She wasn't that great.

248
00:18:00,454 --> 00:18:01,788
<font color=#ff00ff>[Men chanting]</font> Fresh fish!

249
00:18:01,789 --> 00:18:03,539
<font color=#ff00ff>[Door opens]</font>

250
00:18:03,540 --> 00:18:06,417
What the Christ is this happy horse shit?

251
00:18:06,418 --> 00:18:09,212
He took the Lord's name in vain.
I'm telling the Warden.

252
00:18:09,213 --> 00:18:12,548
- With my baton up your ass!
<font color=#FF551>- FAT ASS:</font> Let me out of here!

253
00:18:12,549 --> 00:18:16,010
What is your malfunction,
you fat barrel of monkey spunk?

254
00:18:16,011 --> 00:18:17,261
<font color=#FF551>FAT ASS:</font> Please...

255
00:18:17,262 --> 00:18:19,388
I ain't supposed to be here.

256
00:18:19,389 --> 00:18:20,848
Not me!

257
00:18:20,849 --> 00:18:23,392
I ain't gonna count to three, or even one.

258
00:18:23,393 --> 00:18:25,770
Shut the fuck up, or I'll sing you a lullaby!

259
00:18:25,771 --> 00:18:27,688
<font color=#ff00ff>[Whispers]</font> Shut up, man. Shut up.

260
00:18:27,689 --> 00:18:29,065
There's been a mistake!

261
00:18:29,066 --> 00:18:32,618
You don't understand.
I'm not supposed to be here!

262
00:18:32,619 --> 00:18:33,486
Open that cell.

263
00:18:33,487 --> 00:18:37,337
<font color=#FF551>MAN:</font> Me neither. You people run
this place like a fucking prison!

264
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:46,650
<font color=#FF551>HADLEY:</font> Son of a bitch.

265
00:18:47,251 --> 00:18:49,210
<font color=#ff00ff>[Thuds]</font>

266
00:18:49,211 --> 00:18:51,337
<font color=#ff00ff>[Whimpering]</font>

267
00:18:51,638 --> 00:18:53,802
<font color=#FF551>PRISONER:</font> Take it easy.

268
00:18:58,762 --> 00:19:00,809
<font color=#ff00ff>[Yelps]</font>

269
00:19:16,196 --> 00:19:19,657
If I hear so much as a mouse
fart in here the rest of the night,

270
00:19:19,658 --> 00:19:23,411
I swear by God and sonny Jesus,
you will all visit the infirmary.

271
00:19:23,412 --> 00:19:25,876
Every last motherfucker in here.

272
00:19:29,418 --> 00:19:33,167
Call the trustees.
Take that tub of shit down to the infirmary.

273
00:19:47,394 --> 00:19:52,190
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> His first night in the joint, Andy
Dufresne cost me two packs of cigarettes.

274
00:19:52,191 --> 00:19:55,447
He never made a sound.

275
00:19:57,946 --> 00:20:00,411
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gate buzzer]</font>

276
00:20:10,584 --> 00:20:16,172
<font color=#FF551>- GUARD:</font> Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Tier 2 South. Clear.

277
00:20:16,173 --> 00:20:20,176
- Tier 3 South. Clear.
- Tier 1 North...

278
00:20:20,177 --> 00:20:23,054
- Tier 1 South. Clear.
- Tier 4 South. Clear.

279
00:20:23,255 --> 00:20:25,519
Prepare to roll out.

280
00:20:28,518 --> 00:20:30,183
<font color=#FF551>GUARD:</font> Roll out!

281
00:21:23,490 --> 00:21:26,367
Are... Are you going to eat that?

282
00:21:26,368 --> 00:21:29,667
I hadn't... I hadn't planned on it.

283
00:21:30,539 --> 00:21:31,960
Do you mind?

284
00:21:38,922 --> 00:21:41,929
Ah... that's nice and ripe.

285
00:21:46,305 --> 00:21:48,769
<font color=#ff00ff>[Chirps]</font>

286
00:21:53,145 --> 00:21:55,388
Jake says thank you.

287
00:21:55,689 --> 00:21:58,587
Fell out of his nest over by the plate shop.

288
00:22:00,360 --> 00:22:04,089
I'm going to look after him
until he's big enough to fly.

289
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:07,162
Oh, no, no. Here he comes.

290
00:22:09,911 --> 00:22:13,514
Morning, fellas. Fine morning, ain't it?

291
00:22:13,915 --> 00:22:16,417
You know why it's a fine morning, don't you?

292
00:22:16,418 --> 00:22:18,919
Come on. Set 'em down.
I want 'em all lined up here,

293
00:22:18,920 --> 00:22:21,197
just like a pretty little chorus line.

294
00:22:22,498 --> 00:22:23,966
Yeah, look at that!

295
00:22:23,967 --> 00:22:26,927
- Look at that.       - I can't stand this guy.
-  Oh, Lord!

296
00:22:26,928 --> 00:22:28,054
<font color=#ff00ff>[Inhales]</font>

297
00:22:28,055 --> 00:22:30,806
Yes. Richmond, Virginia.

298
00:22:30,807 --> 00:22:33,975
- Smell my ass!
- After he smells mine.

299
00:22:33,976 --> 00:22:38,397
Gee, Red, it was a terrible shame
about your horse coming in last, an' all.

300
00:22:38,698 --> 00:22:41,692
But I sure do love that winning
horse of mine, though.

301
00:22:41,693 --> 00:22:45,087
I believe, I owe that boy a great big,
sloppy kiss when I see him.

302
00:22:45,088 --> 00:22:47,573
Why don't you give him some
of your cigarettes, instead?

303
00:22:47,574 --> 00:22:49,150
Lucky fuck.

304
00:22:49,751 --> 00:22:51,043
Hey, Tyrell.

305
00:22:51,244 --> 00:22:53,188
You pull infirmary duty this week?

306
00:22:54,289 --> 00:22:57,625
- How's that horse of mine doing, anyway?
- Dead.

307
00:22:58,126 --> 00:23:03,005
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.
The doc had already gone home for the night.

308
00:23:03,306 --> 00:23:05,841
Poor bastard lay there till this morning.

309
00:23:05,842 --> 00:23:08,657
By then, hell, there weren't
nothing we could do.

310
00:23:14,476 --> 00:23:16,440
What was his name?

311
00:23:19,314 --> 00:23:21,069
What did you say?

312
00:23:22,567 --> 00:23:25,027
I was just wondering if
anyone knew his name.

313
00:23:25,828 --> 00:23:28,118
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

314
00:23:29,199 --> 00:23:32,456
It doesn't fuckin' matter what
his name was. He's dead.

315
00:23:51,930 --> 00:23:53,048
Hey...

316
00:23:54,349 --> 00:23:56,581
Anybody come at you yet?

317
00:23:58,603 --> 00:24:00,984
Anybody get to you yet?

318
00:24:02,231 --> 00:24:04,859
Hey, we all need friends in here.

319
00:24:05,160 --> 00:24:06,857
I could be a friend to you.

320
00:24:09,839 --> 00:24:11,086
Hey...

321
00:24:15,745 --> 00:24:17,501
Hard to get.

322
00:24:19,291 --> 00:24:20,838
I like that.

323
00:24:27,591 --> 00:24:30,968
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Andy kept pretty
much to himself at first.

324
00:24:31,369 --> 00:24:36,403
I guess he had a lot on his mind,
trying to adapt to life on the inside.

325
00:24:37,267 --> 00:24:40,160
It wasn't until a month went by
that he opened his mouth...

326
00:24:40,161 --> 00:24:42,734
to say more than two words to somebody.

327
00:24:44,274 --> 00:24:48,199
As it turned out... that somebody was me.

328
00:24:51,707 --> 00:24:55,056
<font color=#FF551>TANNOY:</font> Officers Russell and Burwell
report to the duty officer.

329
00:24:57,120 --> 00:24:58,955
I'm Andy Dufresne.

330
00:24:59,956 --> 00:25:01,921
The wife-killing banker.

331
00:25:04,077 --> 00:25:05,169
Why did you do it?

332
00:25:05,870 --> 00:25:07,379
I didn't, since you ask.

333
00:25:07,380 --> 00:25:10,008
<font color=#ff00ff>[Laughs]</font> You're gonna fit right in!

334
00:25:10,509 --> 00:25:12,961
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

335
00:25:13,562 --> 00:25:17,077
- Heywood, what are you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

336
00:25:20,218 --> 00:25:22,395
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

337
00:25:22,796 --> 00:25:26,232
You think your shit smells
sweeter than most. Is that right?

338
00:25:26,733 --> 00:25:29,651
- What do you think?
- To tell you the truth,

339
00:25:29,752 --> 00:25:32,321
I haven't made up my mind. <font color=#ff00ff>[Chuckles]</font>

340
00:25:32,522 --> 00:25:35,392
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

341
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:39,579
I'm known to locate certain
things, from time to time.

342
00:25:40,080 --> 00:25:42,665
- I wonder if you might get me
a rock hammer.        - A what?

343
00:25:43,166 --> 00:25:44,625
A rock hammer.

344
00:25:45,126 --> 00:25:47,299
- What is it, and why?
- What do you care?

345
00:25:48,797 --> 00:25:51,857
Well, if it was a toothbrush, I would'nt
a question, I'd just quote a price,

346
00:25:51,858 --> 00:25:54,523
but then a toothbrush is
a non-lethal object, is'nt it?

347
00:25:55,762 --> 00:25:56,955
Fair enough.

348
00:25:57,556 --> 00:26:00,299
A rock hammer is about
six or seven inches long.

349
00:26:00,550 --> 00:26:02,818
- Looks like a miniature pickaxe.
- Pickaxe?

350
00:26:02,819 --> 00:26:04,984
- For rocks.
- Rocks.

351
00:26:06,773 --> 00:26:07,924
Quartz?

352
00:26:09,225 --> 00:26:10,373
Quartz.

353
00:26:11,945 --> 00:26:14,005
And some mica.

354
00:26:14,606 --> 00:26:15,953
Shale.

355
00:26:16,658 --> 00:26:18,125
Limestone.

356
00:26:18,326 --> 00:26:19,227
So?

357
00:26:20,328 --> 00:26:21,996
So, I'm a rock hound.

358
00:26:22,497 --> 00:26:25,891
At least, I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again on a limited basis.

359
00:26:26,092 --> 00:26:28,502
Or maybe you want
to hammer somebody's skull.

360
00:26:28,903 --> 00:26:29,841
No, sir.

361
00:26:30,589 --> 00:26:32,256
I have no enemies here.

362
00:26:32,257 --> 00:26:35,013
No? Wait a while.

363
00:26:36,177 --> 00:26:37,529
Word gets around.

364
00:26:38,430 --> 00:26:40,740
The Sisters have taken quite a liking to you.

365
00:26:42,601 --> 00:26:43,814
Especially Bogs.

366
00:26:44,919 --> 00:26:48,814
I don't suppose it would help any
if I explained to them I'm not homosexual.

367
00:26:48,815 --> 00:26:50,399
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Neither are they.

368
00:26:50,400 --> 00:26:53,490
You have to be human first.
They don't qualify.

369
00:26:58,565 --> 00:27:02,495
Bull queers take by force.
It's all they want or understand.

370
00:27:02,996 --> 00:27:06,207
If I were you, I'd grow eyes
in the back of my head.

371
00:27:06,708 --> 00:27:08,125
Thanks for the advice.

372
00:27:08,126 --> 00:27:09,493
Well, that's free.

373
00:27:09,794 --> 00:27:11,629
You understand my concern.

374
00:27:12,130 --> 00:27:15,457
Well, if there's any trouble,
I won't use the hammer, ok?

375
00:27:15,658 --> 00:27:19,349
Then I guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

376
00:27:20,430 --> 00:27:22,306
Did I miss something? What's funny?

377
00:27:22,307 --> 00:27:25,231
You'll understand when
you see the rock hammer.

378
00:27:27,228 --> 00:27:31,941
- What's an item like this usually go for?
- Seven dollars in any rock and gem shop.

379
00:27:32,442 --> 00:27:34,652
My normal mark-up's 20 per cent.

380
00:27:35,253 --> 00:27:37,280
But this is a specialty item.

381
00:27:37,781 --> 00:27:39,865
The risk goes up, the price goes up.

382
00:27:40,367 --> 00:27:42,409
Let's make it an even ten bucks.

383
00:27:42,510 --> 00:27:43,465
Ten it is.

384
00:27:45,372 --> 00:27:47,173
Waste of money, if you ask me.

385
00:27:47,874 --> 00:27:48,796
Why's that?

386
00:27:50,502 --> 00:27:53,425
Folks around this joint
love surprise inspections.

387
00:27:55,131 --> 00:27:56,708
If they find it, you're gonna lose it.

388
00:27:57,509 --> 00:27:59,518
If they do catch you with it,
you don't know me.

389
00:27:59,919 --> 00:28:02,312
You mention my name, we
never do business again.

390
00:28:02,613 --> 00:28:05,020
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now, you got that?

391
00:28:06,643 --> 00:28:07,643
I understand.

392
00:28:09,144 --> 00:28:09,561
Thank you...

393
00:28:10,562 --> 00:28:11,671
Mr. er...?

394
00:28:11,672 --> 00:28:14,858
- Red. The name's Red.
- Red?

395
00:28:15,859 --> 00:28:17,591
Why do they call you that?

396
00:28:21,282 --> 00:28:23,247
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

397
00:28:31,334 --> 00:28:34,461
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I could see why some of
the boys took him for snobby.

398
00:28:35,262 --> 00:28:37,465
He had a quiet way about him.

399
00:28:37,966 --> 00:28:42,111
A walk and a talk, that just
wasn't normal around here.

400
00:28:42,512 --> 00:28:43,638
He strolled...

401
00:28:44,139 --> 00:28:48,059
like a man in a park, without
a care or worry in the world.

402
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:53,055
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

403
00:28:53,556 --> 00:28:57,526
Yeah. I think it would be fair to say...

404
00:28:57,727 --> 00:28:59,491
I liked Andy from the start.

405
00:29:01,364 --> 00:29:04,955
Let's go!
Some of us have got a schedule to keep.

406
00:29:08,801 --> 00:29:10,835
Move it! Come on. Move it!

407
00:29:13,585 --> 00:29:17,092
Bob, how are you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

408
00:29:26,431 --> 00:29:27,773
Easy.

409
00:29:28,374 --> 00:29:29,938
Keep it moving.

410
00:29:33,554 --> 00:29:34,484
Red...

411
00:29:54,626 --> 00:29:58,621
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Andy was right. I finally got the joke.

412
00:29:59,122 --> 00:30:03,805
It would take a man about 600 years
to tunnel under the wall with one of these.

413
00:30:07,764 --> 00:30:10,229
- Book?
- Not today.

414
00:30:16,189 --> 00:30:18,153
- Book?
- No.

415
00:30:20,068 --> 00:30:21,656
Hey, Brooksy.

416
00:30:24,572 --> 00:30:27,037
Delivery for Dufresne.

417
00:30:33,748 --> 00:30:39,458
Book?... book?

418
00:30:42,382 --> 00:30:43,791
Dufresne...

419
00:30:44,592 --> 00:30:45,940
Here's your book.

420
00:30:51,182 --> 00:30:52,730
Thanks.

421
00:30:57,688 --> 00:31:02,047
Dufresne! We're running low on Hexlite.
Get on back and fetch us up some.

422
00:31:39,572 --> 00:31:41,315
If you get this in your eyes, it blinds you.

423
00:31:41,316 --> 00:31:44,447
Honey... hush.

424
00:31:51,159 --> 00:31:53,415
<font color=#ff00ff>[Groans]</font>

425
00:31:56,522 --> 00:31:58,624
That's it. You fight.

426
00:31:58,625 --> 00:32:00,292
It's better that way.

427
00:32:00,293 --> 00:32:02,465
<font color=#ff00ff>[Screaming and yelling]</font>

428
00:32:08,635 --> 00:32:11,653
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I wish I could tell you
that Andy fought the good fight,

429
00:32:11,654 --> 00:32:13,681
and the Sisters let him be.

430
00:32:14,182 --> 00:32:16,165
I wish I could tell you that.

431
00:32:16,467 --> 00:32:18,732
But prison is no fairy-tale world.

432
00:32:20,313 --> 00:32:22,022
He never said who did it.

433
00:32:22,523 --> 00:32:24,351
But we all knew.

434
00:32:25,652 --> 00:32:27,907
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gate buzzer]</font>

435
00:32:28,905 --> 00:32:31,365
Things went on like that for a while.

436
00:32:31,866 --> 00:32:34,576
Prison life consists of routine...

437
00:32:34,577 --> 00:32:36,667
and then more routine.

438
00:32:39,165 --> 00:32:42,681
Every so often, Andy would
show up with fresh bruises.

439
00:32:44,170 --> 00:32:45,796
The Sisters kept at him.

440
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:49,909
Sometimes he was able to
fight 'em off. Sometimes not.

441
00:32:51,410 --> 00:32:53,345
And that's how it went for Andy.

442
00:32:53,846 --> 00:32:55,973
That was his routine.

443
00:32:56,474 --> 00:33:00,052
I do believe those first two
years were the worst for him.

444
00:33:00,353 --> 00:33:01,728
And I also believe,

445
00:33:01,729 --> 00:33:06,417
if things had gone on that way, this
place would have got the best of him.

446
00:33:07,318 --> 00:33:12,447
But then, in the spring of 1949,
the powers that be decided that...

447
00:33:12,448 --> 00:33:15,451
The roof of the license-plate
factory needs resurfacing.

448
00:33:16,152 --> 00:33:19,084
I need a dozen volunteers for a week's work.

449
00:33:19,872 --> 00:33:21,282
As you know,

450
00:33:21,783 --> 00:33:25,377
special detail carries with it special privileges.

451
00:33:25,878 --> 00:33:28,243
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> It was outdoor detail...

452
00:33:28,765 --> 00:33:32,835
...and May is one damn fine
month to be working outdoors.

453
00:33:33,136 --> 00:33:34,545
Stay in line there.

454
00:33:35,146 --> 00:33:37,644
More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.

455
00:33:39,267 --> 00:33:41,314
<font color=#ff00ff>[Whispers]</font>

456
00:33:42,145 --> 00:33:44,818
Wallace E Unger.

457
00:33:45,606 --> 00:33:47,750
Ellis Redding.

458
00:33:48,151 --> 00:33:49,769
Wouldn't you know it?

459
00:33:50,370 --> 00:33:53,539
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names called.

460
00:33:53,740 --> 00:33:55,907
<font color=#FF551>GUARD:</font> Andrew Dufresne.

461
00:33:56,408 --> 00:33:58,936
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> It only cost us a pack
of smokes per man.

462
00:33:59,537 --> 00:34:02,330
I made my usual 20 per cent, of course.

463
00:34:02,331 --> 00:34:05,901
<font color=#FF551>HADLEY:</font> So, this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

464
00:34:06,002 --> 00:34:07,294
I say, "Yeah?"

465
00:34:07,795 --> 00:34:11,390
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

466
00:34:11,591 --> 00:34:15,935
- Oh, damn, Byron. I'm sorry to hear that.
- I'm not. He was an asshole.

467
00:34:16,036 --> 00:34:18,055
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead, anyway.

468
00:34:18,056 --> 00:34:22,100
So, anyway, this lawyer fella says to me,
"Your brother died a rich man."

469
00:34:22,101 --> 00:34:27,039
- Oil wells and shit. Close to a million bucks.
<font color=#FF551>- GUARD:</font> A million bucks?

470
00:34:27,840 --> 00:34:29,980
Fucking incredible how
lucky some assholes get.

471
00:34:29,981 --> 00:34:32,127
Jeez-Louise! Are you gonna see any of that?

472
00:34:32,528 --> 00:34:35,397
35,000. That's what he left me.

473
00:34:35,598 --> 00:34:37,199
- Dollars?
- Yeah.

474
