<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Tossing cells was just an excuse.

706
00:51:22,179 --> 00:51:26,044
The truth is, Norton wanted to size Andy up.

707
00:51:39,804 --> 00:51:41,911
My wife made that in church group.

708
00:51:44,768 --> 00:51:46,282
Very nice, sir.

709
00:51:47,570 --> 00:51:49,526
Do you enjoy working in the laundry?

710
00:51:50,774 --> 00:51:52,566
No, sir, not especially.

711
00:51:52,967 --> 00:51:54,944
Perhaps we can find something more...

712
00:51:55,445 --> 00:51:57,910
befitting a man of your education.

713
00:52:01,868 --> 00:52:04,124
<font color=#ff00ff>[Bird screeches]</font>

714
00:52:05,872 --> 00:52:07,623
Hey, Jake. Where's Brooks?

715
00:52:08,124 --> 00:52:08,999
Andy.

716
00:52:09,500 --> 00:52:11,673
I thought I heard you out here!

717
00:52:12,796 --> 00:52:14,463
I've been reassigned to you.

718
00:52:14,864 --> 00:52:17,716
I know. They told me. <font color=#ff00ff>[Chuckles]</font>

719
00:52:17,917 --> 00:52:19,585
Ain't that a kick in the head?

720
00:52:20,186 --> 00:52:22,371
Well, I'll give you the dime tour.

721
00:52:22,572 --> 00:52:23,340
Come on.

722
00:52:25,041 --> 00:52:26,692
Well, here she is.

723
00:52:26,893 --> 00:52:28,920
Shawshank Prison library.

724
00:52:29,521 --> 00:52:31,581
National Geographics.

725
00:52:32,482 --> 00:52:35,401
Reader's Digest condensed books.

726
00:52:35,652 --> 00:52:37,295
Louis L'Amour.

727
00:52:37,696 --> 00:52:39,505
Look Magazine.

728
00:52:39,906 --> 00:52:42,091
Erle Stanley Gardners.

729
00:52:42,492 --> 00:52:45,636
Every evening,
I load up the cart and make my round.

730
00:52:46,237 --> 00:52:48,790
I enter the names on this clipboard here.

731
00:52:49,291 --> 00:52:55,880
- Easy-peasy, Japanesey. Any questions?
- Brooks, how long have you been librarian?

732
00:52:56,281 --> 00:53:01,635
Oh... I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

733
00:53:02,536 --> 00:53:04,797
And in all that time,
have you ever had an assistant?

734
00:53:04,798 --> 00:53:07,565
No. No, not much to it, really.

735
00:53:08,167 --> 00:53:10,753
- Well, why me? Why now?
- I don't know,

736
00:53:11,154 --> 00:53:14,390
but it'll be nice to have some
company down here for a change.

737
00:53:14,391 --> 00:53:15,955
<font color=#FF551>HADLEY:</font> Dufresne!

738
00:53:25,577 --> 00:53:27,641
That's him. That's the one.

739
00:53:35,212 --> 00:53:36,587
I'm Dekins.

740
00:53:36,988 --> 00:53:38,731
<font color=#ff00ff>[Nervously]</font> I was er...

741
00:53:39,132 --> 00:53:43,515
thinking about maybe setting up some
kind of trust fund for my kids' educations.

742
00:53:45,472 --> 00:53:46,714
Oh...

743
00:53:47,015 --> 00:53:48,562
I see.

744
00:53:50,343 --> 00:53:51,699
Well, erm...

745
00:53:53,396 --> 00:53:56,487
...why don't we have a seat, and talk it over?

746
00:53:59,453 --> 00:54:02,551
Brooks, do you have
a piece of paper and a pencil?

747
00:54:13,942 --> 00:54:15,134
Thanks.

748
00:54:16,035 --> 00:54:17,483
So...

749
00:54:18,755 --> 00:54:20,440
Mr. Dekins...

750
00:54:21,341 --> 00:54:25,886
And then Andy says to Mr. Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

751
00:54:25,887 --> 00:54:28,097
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

752
00:54:28,098 --> 00:54:30,849
As God is my witness, he did!

753
00:54:31,150 --> 00:54:34,511
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

754
00:54:34,512 --> 00:54:36,772
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

755
00:54:36,773 --> 00:54:37,731
My ass!

756
00:54:37,732 --> 00:54:39,024
Shook his hand.

757
00:54:39,025 --> 00:54:42,569
Hell, I... I near soiled myself! <font color=#ff00ff>[Laughs]</font>

758
00:54:42,570 --> 00:54:46,865
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

759
00:54:46,866 --> 00:54:49,410
and he would have been:
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please"!

760
00:54:49,411 --> 00:54:51,541
Making a few friends, Andy?

761
00:54:52,205 --> 00:54:54,248
I wouldn't say "friends".

762
00:54:54,549 --> 00:54:58,135
I'm a convicted murderer who
provides sound financial planning.

763
00:54:58,136 --> 00:55:00,254
It's a wonderful pet to have.

764
00:55:00,955 --> 00:55:05,050
- Got you out of the laundry, though.
- Well, it might do more than that.

765
00:55:05,251 --> 00:55:08,137
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

766
00:55:08,138 --> 00:55:10,931
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

767
00:55:11,832 --> 00:55:14,375
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

768
00:55:14,376 --> 00:55:18,814
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr. Dufresne, if you please?

769
00:55:19,315 --> 00:55:20,649
Ask the Warden for funds.

770
00:55:20,650 --> 00:55:21,984
<font color=#ff00ff>[Laughter]</font>

771
00:55:21,985 --> 00:55:25,762
Son, son, son. Six wardens have
been through here in my tenure,

772
00:55:25,763 --> 00:55:28,474
and I've learned one
immutable, universal truth.

773
00:55:28,775 --> 00:55:30,384
Not one of them born...

774
00:55:30,785 --> 00:55:33,327
whose asshole wouldn't pucker
up tighter than a snare...

775
00:55:33,328 --> 00:55:34,931
...drum when you asked them for funds.

776
00:55:36,632 --> 00:55:39,043
- The budget's stretched thin, as it is.
- I see.

777
00:55:39,544 --> 00:55:43,172
Perhaps I could write to the State
Senate and request funds from them.

778
00:55:43,373 --> 00:55:45,255
As far as they're concerned,
there's only three ways to spend...

779
00:55:45,256 --> 00:55:47,434
...tax paying hard than money
when it comes to prisons.

780
00:55:47,835 --> 00:55:49,903
more walls, more bars and more guards.

781
00:55:49,904 --> 00:55:54,608
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission. A
letter a week. They can't ignore me forever.

782
00:55:54,609 --> 00:55:55,434
Sure can.

783
00:55:56,135 --> 00:55:58,396
But you write your letters,
if it makes you happy.

784
00:55:58,897 --> 00:56:01,570
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

785
00:56:03,309 --> 00:56:08,002
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> So, Andy started writing
a letter a week,... just like he said.

786
00:56:12,369 --> 00:56:16,877
And, just like Norton said,
Andy got no answers.

787
00:56:24,539 --> 00:56:29,427
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

788
00:56:30,928 --> 00:56:33,097
The year after that, he did them all...

789
00:56:33,098 --> 00:56:35,062
including the Warden's.

790
00:56:37,259 --> 00:56:40,396
The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season

791
00:56:40,397 --> 00:56:42,861
to coincide with tax season.

792
00:56:44,776 --> 00:56:49,071
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

793
00:56:49,072 --> 00:56:53,383
So, Moresby Prison issued you
your gun, but you had to pay for it?

794
00:56:53,384 --> 00:56:55,119
Damn right. The holster, too.

795
00:56:55,120 --> 00:56:57,704
That's tax-deductible. You can write that off.

796
00:56:57,705 --> 00:57:01,125
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Yes, sir. Andy was a
regular cottage industry.

797
00:57:01,626 --> 00:57:04,253
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

798
00:57:04,254 --> 00:57:06,180
he was allowed a staff.

799
00:57:06,581 --> 00:57:08,924
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

800
00:57:09,125 --> 00:57:11,677
It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,

801
00:57:11,678 --> 00:57:13,830
and that was fine by me.

802
00:57:15,231 --> 00:57:18,188
And still... he kept sending those letters.

803
00:57:23,106 --> 00:57:25,023
Red,... Andy.

804
00:57:25,024 --> 00:57:26,316
It's Brooks.

805
00:57:26,317 --> 00:57:28,361
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Men shouting]</font>
- Watch the door.

806
00:57:28,862 --> 00:57:31,929
- Please, Brooks.
- Just calm the fuck down.

807
00:57:31,930 --> 00:57:32,614
Stay back!

808
00:57:33,015 --> 00:57:34,841
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

809
00:57:34,842 --> 00:57:37,911
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

810
00:57:38,212 --> 00:57:40,456
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

811
00:57:40,457 --> 00:57:42,666
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

812
00:57:42,667 --> 00:57:44,460
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

813
00:57:44,461 --> 00:57:46,420
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

814
00:57:46,421 --> 00:57:48,030
It's what they done!

815
00:57:48,931 --> 00:57:50,332
I... I got no choice...

816
00:57:50,333 --> 00:57:53,285
You're not gonna hurt Heywood.
we all know even Heywood knows that.

817
00:57:53,286 --> 00:57:55,496
- Right, Heywood?
- I... I know that, sure.

818
00:57:55,497 --> 00:57:59,199
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend of
yours and Brooks has been a reasonable man.

819
00:57:59,200 --> 00:58:00,476
That's right. That's right, guys?

820
00:58:00,477 --> 00:58:04,137
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

821
00:58:04,138 --> 00:58:05,852
Put the knife down.

822
00:58:06,858 --> 00:58:07,808
Brooks...

823
00:58:08,309 --> 00:58:10,044
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

824
00:58:11,345 --> 00:58:12,863
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

825
00:58:12,864 --> 00:58:14,114
<font color=#ff00ff>[Heywood gasps]</font>

826
00:58:14,115 --> 00:58:15,282
It's the only...

827
00:58:16,183 --> 00:58:18,160
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

828
00:58:18,161 --> 00:58:20,746
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this, come on.

829
00:58:21,147 --> 00:58:22,711
Put it down.

830
00:58:24,167 --> 00:58:26,923
<font color=#ff00ff>[Brooks sobs]</font>

831
00:58:30,415 --> 00:58:35,010
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

832
00:58:35,511 --> 00:58:36,270
<font color=#FF551>HEYWOOD:</font> Him?

833
00:58:36,571 --> 00:58:40,624
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

834
00:58:40,625 --> 00:58:42,935
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

835
00:58:43,236 --> 00:58:44,870
What the hell did you
do to set him off, anyway?

836
00:58:44,871 --> 00:58:47,689
I do nothing. I come in
here to say fare-thee-well.

837
00:58:48,290 --> 00:58:50,697
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

838
00:58:53,262 --> 00:58:55,973
I just don't understand what
happened in there. That's all.

839
00:58:55,974 --> 00:58:58,942
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

840
00:58:58,943 --> 00:59:01,036
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

841
00:59:01,437 --> 00:59:04,222
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

842
00:59:04,223 --> 00:59:05,582
Would you knock it off?

843
00:59:06,483 --> 00:59:08,001
Brooks ain't no bug.

844
00:59:08,502 --> 00:59:09,458
He's just...

845
00:59:11,756 --> 00:59:13,970
He's just institutionalized.

846
00:59:14,926 --> 00:59:17,177
Institutionalized, my ass.

847
00:59:17,178 --> 00:59:21,056
The man's been in here
50 years, Heywood. 50 years.

848
00:59:21,057 --> 00:59:22,549
This is all he knows.

849
00:59:23,250 --> 00:59:25,352
In here, he's an important man.

850
00:59:25,693 --> 00:59:26,895
He's an educated man.

851
00:59:27,696 --> 00:59:29,361
Outside, he's nothing.

852
00:59:30,350 --> 00:59:33,360
Just a used-up con with
arthritis in both hands.

853
00:59:34,061 --> 00:59:36,655
Probably couldn't get
a library card if he tried.

854
00:59:37,256 --> 00:59:38,824
You know what I'm trying to say?

855
00:59:39,525 --> 00:59:42,257
Red, I do believe you're
talking out of your ass.

856
00:59:43,729 --> 00:59:45,748
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

857
00:59:46,449 --> 00:59:48,672
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

858
00:59:50,411 --> 00:59:51,976
First you hate 'em...

859
00:59:54,140 --> 00:59:55,804
...then you get used to 'em.

860
00:59:57,752 --> 00:59:59,762
Enough time passes...

861
01:00:00,463 --> 01:00:02,607
you get so you depend on 'em.

862
01:00:03,408 --> 01:00:05,526
That's institutionalized.

863
01:00:06,027 --> 01:00:07,102
<font color=#FF551>JIGGER:</font> Shit.

864
01:00:07,103 --> 01:00:08,812
You can never get like that.

865
01:00:08,813 --> 01:00:10,314
Oh, yeah?

866
01:00:11,015 --> 01:00:13,483
Say that when you've been
here as long as Brooks has.

867
01:00:13,784 --> 01:00:15,240
Goddamn right.

868
01:00:17,697 --> 01:00:19,624
They send you here for life.

869
01:00:20,675 --> 01:00:22,789
That's exactly what they take.

870
01:00:24,529 --> 01:00:26,293
The part that counts, anyway.

871
01:00:28,459 --> 01:00:33,174
<font color=#ff00ff>[Jake screeches]</font>

872
01:00:33,921 --> 01:00:36,669
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

873
01:00:38,209 --> 01:00:39,723
You go on, now.

874
01:00:41,128 --> 01:00:42,479
You're free.

875
01:00:44,028 --> 01:00:44,979
You're free.

876
01:01:01,891 --> 01:01:03,247
Bye.

877
01:01:04,452 --> 01:01:06,250
Good luck, Brooks.

878
01:01:44,349 --> 01:01:45,742
<font color=#FF551>BROOKS:</font> Dear fellas...

879
01:01:46,243 --> 01:01:50,238
I can't believe how fast
things move on the outside.

880
01:01:50,239 --> 01:01:51,373
<font color=#ff00ff>[Horn blares]</font>

881
01:01:51,774 --> 01:01:54,101
Watch it, old-timer! Are
you trying to get killed?

882
01:01:55,402 --> 01:01:58,921
I saw an automobile once,
when I was a kid, but...

883
01:01:59,522 --> 01:02:01,721
now... they're everywhere.

884
01:02:05,454 --> 01:02:09,320
The world went and got
itself in a big damn hurry.

885
01:02:25,991 --> 01:02:31,771
The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,

886
01:02:31,772 --> 01:02:35,747
and a job, bagging groceries at the Foodway.

887
01:02:37,411 --> 01:02:42,832
It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.

888
01:02:42,833 --> 01:02:44,818
<font color=#FF551>WOMAN:</font> Make sure your man double-bags.

889
01:02:44,819 --> 01:02:47,853
Last time, he didn't double-bags.
The bottom near came out.

890
01:02:47,854 --> 01:02:50,932
Make sure you double-bag,
like the lady says. Understand?

891
01:02:50,933 --> 01:02:52,275
Yes, sir. I surely will.

892
01:02:52,276 --> 01:02:55,854
<font color=#FF551>BROOKS:</font> I don't think the store
manager likes me very much.

893
01:02:55,855 --> 01:02:58,027
<font color=#ff00ff>[Pigeons cooing]</font>

894
01:02:59,133 --> 01:03:03,612
Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

895
01:03:03,913 --> 01:03:09,034
I keep thinking... Jake might
just show up and say hello.

896
01:03:09,335 --> 01:03:11,207
But he never does.

897
01:03:12,613 --> 01:03:17,672
And I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.

898
01:03:21,097 --> 01:03:23,799
I have trouble sleeping at night.

899
01:03:24,200 --> 01:03:26,973
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

900
01:03:27,978 --> 01:03:29,979
I wake up, scared.

901
01:03:30,180 --> 01:03:34,163
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

902
01:03:35,811 --> 01:03:41,256
Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

903
01:03:41,317 --> 01:03:43,535
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

904
01:03:43,736 --> 01:03:45,575
Sort of like a bonus.

905
01:03:47,097 --> 01:03:51,034
I guess I'm too old for that
sort of nonsense any more.

906
01:03:51,535 --> 01:03:53,161
I don't like it here.

907
01:03:53,162 --> 01:03:55,914
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

908
01:03:56,315 --> 01:03:57,382
I've decided...

909
01:03:57,983 --> 01:03:59,339
not to stay.

910
01:04:10,504 --> 01:04:16,456
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

911
01:04:30,825 --> 01:04:33,122
<font color=#ff00ff>[Scraping]</font>

912
01:05:19,598 --> 01:05:23,623
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

913
01:05:24,511 --> 01:05:28,556
PS. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

914
01:05:28,557 --> 01:05:30,422
No hard feelings. Brooks."

915
01:05:41,362 --> 01:05:43,026
He should have died in here.

916
01:05:48,669 --> 01:05:52,611
<font color=#FF551>HADLEY:</font> What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

917
01:05:58,645 --> 01:05:59,545
What's all this?

918
01:05:59,546 --> 01:06:02,108
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

919
01:06:03,789 --> 01:06:04,981
Take it.

920
01:06:13,469 --> 01:06:15,233
"Dear Mr. Dufresne...

921
01:06:16,138 --> 01:06:18,523
In response to your repeated enquiries,

922
01:06:18,524 --> 01:06:22,519
the State has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

923
01:06:23,820 --> 01:06:24,776
This is 200 dollars.

924
01:06:25,539 --> 01:06:29,142
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

925
01:06:29,143 --> 01:06:32,237
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

926
01:06:32,538 --> 01:06:34,406
We trust this will fill your needs.

927
01:06:34,807 --> 01:06:38,818
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

928
01:06:39,019 --> 01:06:41,738
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

929
01:06:41,739 --> 01:06:42,586
Yes, sir.

930
01:06:47,361 --> 01:06:48,716
Good for you, Andy.

931
01:06:51,365 --> 01:06:52,304
Wow!

932
01:06:53,709 --> 01:06:55,473
It only took six years.

933
01:06:57,287 --> 01:06:59,998
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week, instead of one.

934
01:06:59,999 --> 01:07:03,576
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out here,

935
01:07:03,577 --> 01:07:04,628
like the Captain said.

936
01:07:05,029 --> 01:07:09,786
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

937
01:07:15,080 --> 01:07:16,161
Wow.

938
01:07:46,854 --> 01:07:49,444
<font color=#ff00ff>[MOZART, "Duettino from
The Marriage Of Figaro"]</font>

939
01:07:51,025 --> 01:07:53,990
<i># Sull'aria... #</i>

940
01:07:58,139 --> 01:07:59,541
Andy, do you hear that?

941
01:07:59,742 --> 01:08:03,833
<i># ...zeffiretto #</i>

942
01:08:11,921 --> 01:08:14,135
<font color=#ff00ff>[Locks door]</font>

943
01:08:15,674 --> 01:08:23,895
<i># Questa sera spirera #</i>

944
01:08:32,233 --> 01:08:33,946
<font color=#ff00ff>[Feedback hisses]</font>

945
01:08:35,778 --> 01:08:39,076
<font color=#ff00ff>[Music over loudspeakers]</font>

946
01:08:42,701 --> 01:08:45,166
<font color=#ff00ff>[Aria continues]</font>

947
01:08:54,121 --> 01:08:58,299
<i># Sotto i pini #</i>

948
01:08:58,300 --> 01:09:03,893
<i># Del boschetto #</i>

949
01:09:05,215 --> 01:09:07,475
<i># Sotto i pini... #</i>

950
01:09:07,476 --> 01:09:09,936
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Banging at door]</font>
- Dufresne?

951
01:09:10,737 --> 01:09:11,505
Dufresne?

952
01:09:12,406 --> 01:09:13,870
Andy, let me out.

953
01:09:17,002 --> 01:09:18,130
Andy?

954
01:09:20,731 --> 01:09:25,485
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I have no idea to this day what
those two Italian ladies were singing about.

955
01:09:26,186 --> 01:09:28,488
The truth is, I don't want to know.

956
01:09:28,789 --> 01:09:30,953
Some things are best left unsaid.

957
01:09:34,620 --> 01:09:37,321
I like to think they were singing
about something so beautiful,...

958
01:09:37,322 --> 01:09:42,506
...it can't be expressed in words,... and
makes your heart ache because of it.

959
01:09:44,338 --> 01:09:47,031
I tell you, those voices soared...

960
01:09:47,032 --> 01:09:51,361
higher and farther than anybody
in a grey place dares to dream.

961
01:09:51,762 --> 01:09:55,203
It was like some beautiful bird
flapped into our drab little cage

962
01:09:55,204 --> 01:09:57,734
and made those walls dissolve away.

963
01:09:58,435 --> 01:10:00,153
And for the briefest of moments...

964
01:10:00,754 --> 01:10:03,920
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

965
01:10:06,643 --> 01:10:09,125
It pissed the Warden off something awful.

966
01:10:10,564 --> 01:10:11,869
Open the door.

967
01:10:14,143 --> 01:10:15,840
Open it up!

968
01:10:17,571 --> 01:10:19,831
Dufresne, open this door!

969
01:10:19,832 --> 01:10:21,374
<font color=#ff00ff>[Bangs door]</font>

970
01:10:21,375 --> 01:10:22,792
Turn that off!

971
01:10:22,793 --> 01:10:25,257
<font color=#ff00ff>[Bangs door]</font>

972
01:10:26,547 --> 01:10:29,507
<font color=#ff00ff>[Aria continues]</font>

973
01:10:29,708 --> 01:10:32,840
I am warning you, Dufresne. Turn that off!

974
01:10:35,764 --> 01:10:38,229
<font color=#ff00ff>[Increases volume]</font>

975
01:10:46,108 --> 01:10:47,464
Dufresne...

976
01:10:49,911 --> 01:10:51,375
You're mine now.

977
01:10:58,845 --> 01:11:01,881
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Andy got two weeks in
the hole for that little stunt.

978
01:11:01,882 --> 01:11:03,680
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Hadley stops record]</font>
- On your feet!

979
01:11:05,310 --> 01:11:07,275
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

980
01:11:08,897 --> 01:11:13,025
Y-Y-You couldn't play something good, huh?
Hank Williams or something?

981
01:11:13,026 --> 01:11:15,778
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

982
01:11:15,779 --> 01:11:17,655
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

983
01:11:17,656 --> 01:11:18,990
Easiest time I ever did.

984
01:11:18,991 --> 01:11:22,034
Bullshit! There's no such
thing as easy time in the hole.

985
01:11:22,035 --> 01:11:24,245
A week in the hole is like a year.

986
01:11:24,746 --> 01:11:27,040
I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

987
01:11:27,541 --> 01:11:29,956
So, they let you tote that
record player down there, huh?

988
01:11:33,005 --> 01:11:34,214
It was in here.

989
01:11:34,715 --> 01:11:36,262
And in here.

990
01:11:37,593 --> 01:11:41,726
That's the beauty of music.
They can't get that from you.

991
01:11:45,767 --> 01:11:47,649
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

992
01:11:49,938 --> 01:11:52,708
Well, I played a mean harmonica,
as a younger man.

993
01:11:54,109 --> 01:11:55,485
Lost interest in it, though.

994
01:11:55,986 --> 01:11:57,403
Didn't make much sense in here.

995
01:11:57,904 --> 01:11:59,548
Here's where it makes the most sense.

996
01:12:00,449 --> 01:12:02,417
You need it, so you don't forget.

997
01:12:03,118 --> 01:12:04,035
Forget?

998
01:12:04,536 --> 01:12:06,079
Forget that...

999
01:12:06,580 --> 01:12:08,544
there are places...

1000
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:13,854
...in the world that aren't made
out of stone... that there's a...

1001
01:12:14,755 --> 01:12:16,172
there's something...

1002
01:12:16,573 --> 01:12:19,850
inside that,... they can't get to... that...

1003
01:12:20,191 --> 01:12:21,527
they can't touch.

1004
01:12:22,328 --> 01:12:23,684
It's yours.

1005
01:12:25,123 --> 01:12:26,312
What are you talking about?

1006
01:12:28,000 --> 01:12:29,185
Hope.

1007
01:12:29,986 --> 01:12:31,042
Hope?

1008
01:12:33,398 --> 01:12:34,950
Let me tell you something, my friend.

1009
01:12:36,001 --> 01:12:37,990
Hope is a dangerous thing.

1010
01:12:39,496 --> 01:12:41,619
Hope can drive a man insane.

1011
01:12:42,783 --> 01:12:44,284
It's got no use on the inside.

1012
01:12:44,885 --> 01:12:46,933
You'd better get used to that idea.

1013
01:12:49,673 --> 01:12:51,379
Like Brooks did?

1014
01:13:16,733 --> 01:13:17,655
Sit down.

1015
01:13:22,989 --> 01:13:26,034
It says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

1016
01:13:27,435 --> 01:13:29,245
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1017
01:13:29,746 --> 01:13:30,830
Oh, yes, sir.

1018
01:13:32,231 --> 01:13:33,296
Without a doubt.

1019
01:13:34,559 --> 01:13:36,674
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

1020
01:13:39,181 --> 01:13:41,007
No danger to society here.

1021
01:13:41,608 --> 01:13:43,072
God's honest truth.

1022
01:13:45,829 --> 01:13:47,593
Absolutely rehabilitated.

1023
01:13:57,741 --> 01:13:59,005
30 years.

1024
01:14:01,111 --> 01:14:02,737
Jesus, when they say it like that...

1025
01:14:03,938 --> 01:14:05,202
You wonder where it went.

1026
01:14:08,085 --> 01:14:09,749
I wonder where ten years went.

1027
01:14:15,217 --> 01:14:16,292
Here.

1028
01:14:16,793 --> 01:14:18,841
Little parole rejection present.

1029
01:14:20,797 --> 01:14:22,023
Go ahead and open it.

1030
01:14:23,824 --> 01:14:26,802
I had to go through one of your
competitors. I hope you don't mind.

1031
01:14:26,803 --> 01:14:28,268
I wanted it to be a surprise.

1032
01:14:39,024 --> 01:14:40,388
It's very pretty, Andy.

1033
01:14:42,194 --> 01:14:43,358
Thank you.

1034
01:14:45,831 --> 01:14:47,195
Are you going to play it?

1035
01:14:52,045 --> 01:14:53,110
No.

1036
01:14:56,525 --> 01:14:58,089
Not right now.

1037
01:15:03,840 --> 01:15:05,466
<font color=#ff00ff>[Guards shout]</font>

1038
01:15:05,967 --> 01:15:07,932
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1039
01:15:09,095 --> 01:15:10,722
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1040
01:15:11,223 --> 01:15:13,187
Tier 1 South. Clear.

1041
01:15:16,144 --> 01:15:17,009
Fall in!

1042
01:15:20,941 --> 01:15:22,905
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gate buzzer]</font>

1043
01:15:50,679 --> 01:15:52,305
<font color=#ff00ff>[Guard's footsteps]</font>

1044
01:15:53,106 --> 01:15:53,973
Lights out!

1045
01:15:54,474 --> 01:15:55,855
<font color=#ff00ff>[Click of light switches]</font>

1046
01:16:01,398 --> 01:16:03,362
<font color=#ff00ff>[Guard walks away]</font>

1047
01:16:09,656 --> 01:16:11,620
<font color=#ff00ff>[Outer door closes]</font>

1048
01:16:20,584 --> 01:16:22,548
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gently plays one note]</font>

1049
01:16:28,091 --> 01:16:28,800
<font color=#ff00ff>[Hammering]</font>

1050
01:16:29,301 --> 01:16:30,927
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Andy was as good as his word.

1051
01:16:31,528 --> 01:16:33,909
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

1052
01:16:36,558 --> 01:16:40,369
In 1959, the State Senate
finally clued into the fact

1053
01:16:40,370 --> 01:16:43,531
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

1054
01:16:43,932 --> 01:16:50,404
Appropriations Committee voted an
annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.

1055
01:16:50,605 --> 01:16:53,449
And you'd be amazed how
far Andy could stretch it.

1056
01:16:53,950 --> 01:16:56,911
He made deals with book
clubs, charity groups.

1057
01:16:56,912 --> 01:16:59,371
He bought remaindered books by the pound.

1058
01:17:00,372 --> 01:17:01,665
Treasure Island.

1059
01:17:02,066 --> 01:17:03,818
Robert Louis...

1060
01:17:03,819 --> 01:17:04,710
...Stevenson.

1061
01:17:05,211 --> 01:17:06,850
Fiction, adventure.

1062
01:17:08,873 --> 01:17:09,999
What's next?

1063
01:17:10,300 --> 01:17:13,190
I got here Auto Repair and...

1064
01:17:14,054 --> 01:17:15,271
...Soap Carving.

1065
01:17:15,472 --> 01:17:18,933
Trade skills and hobbies. Goes under
Educational. The stack behind you.

1066
01:17:18,934 --> 01:17:20,960
The Count Of Monte Crisco.

1067
01:17:21,061 --> 01:17:23,279
That's Cristo, you dumb shit.

1068
01:17:23,580 --> 01:17:27,158
By Alexandree... Dumass.

1069
01:17:27,759 --> 01:17:29,159
Dumb-ass?

1070
01:17:31,059 --> 01:17:32,159
Dumb-ass?

1071
01:17:34,783 --> 01:17:37,101
Dumas. You know what that's about?

1072
01:17:37,502 --> 01:17:38,161
Uh-uh.

1073
01:17:39,062 --> 01:17:41,255
You'll like it. It's about a prison break.

1074
01:17:41,456 --> 01:17:44,842
We ought to file that under
Educational, too, oughtn't we?

1075
01:17:46,243 --> 01:17:49,893
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> The rest of us did our best to
pitch in when and where we could.

1076
01:17:50,966 --> 01:17:52,683
By the year Kennedy was shot,

1077
01:17:52,884 --> 01:17:57,521
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of rat turds and turpentine

1078
01:17:57,522 --> 01:18:00,641
into the best prison library in New England,

1079
01:18:01,242 --> 01:18:04,503
complete with a fine
selection of Hank Williams.

1080
01:18:04,904 --> 01:18:08,357
<i># Lawd I don't know what I'll do-ooo #</i>

1081
01:18:08,658 --> 01:18:11,494
<i># All I do is sit and sigh... #</i>

1082
01:18:11,895 --> 01:18:16,732
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> That was also the year Warden Norton
instituted his famous Inside Out program.

1083
01:18:17,233 --> 01:18:19,326
You may remember reading about it.

1084
01:18:19,727 --> 01:18:22,630
It made all the papers and got
his picture in Look Magazine.

1085
01:18:22,631 --> 01:18:24,081
No free ride.

1086
01:18:24,582 --> 01:18:29,975
But rather a genuine, progressive advance,
in corrections and rehabilitation.

1087
01:18:30,739 --> 01:18:33,157
Our inmates, properly supervised,

1088
01:18:33,558 --> 01:18:35,993
will be put to work outside these walls,

1089
01:18:36,394 --> 01:18:38,562
performing all manner of public service.

1090
01:18:39,163 --> 01:18:42,266
These men can learn the
value of an honest day's labor,

1091
01:18:42,467 --> 01:18:46,020
while providing a valuable
service to the community and...

1092
01:18:46,521 --> 01:18:51,316
at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q Taxpayer.

1093
01:18:51,317 --> 01:18:54,069
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Of course, Norton failed
to mention to the press

1094
01:18:54,070 --> 01:18:57,448
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1095
01:18:58,149 --> 01:19:00,701
There are a hundred different
ways to skim off the top.

1096
01:19:00,702 --> 01:19:03,208
Men, materials, you name it.

1097
01:19:04,372 --> 01:19:07,207
And, oh, my Lord, how the money rolled in.

1098
01:19:07,208 --> 01:19:09,418
If this keeps up, you'll
put me out of business.

1099
01:19:09,419 --> 01:19:11,670
- Ned!
- This pool of slave labor you've got,

1100
01:19:11,671 --> 01:19:13,797
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1101
01:19:13,798 --> 01:19:17,843
Ned,... we're providing
a valuable community service here.

1102
01:19:17,844 --> 01:19:21,264
Well, that's fine for the papers
but I've got a family to feed.

1103
01:19:21,765 --> 01:19:22,357
Sam...

1104
01:19:24,358 --> 01:19:26,101
Sam, we go back a long way.

1105
01:19:27,202 --> 01:19:31,541
I need this new highway contract.
I don't get it, and I go under. That's a fact.

1106
01:19:32,942 --> 01:19:36,637
You just have some of this fine pie
my missus made especially for you,

1107
01:19:37,238 --> 01:19:38,752
and you think about that.

1108
01:19:46,623 --> 01:19:49,125
Ned, I wouldn't worry too
much about this contract.

1109
01:19:49,626 --> 01:19:52,716
It seems to me I already got
my boys committed elsewhere.

1110
01:19:54,714 --> 01:19:57,379
You be sure and thank
Maisie for this fine pie.

1111
01:19:58,927 --> 01:20:00,978
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> And behind every shady deal,

1112
01:20:01,279 --> 01:20:03,472
behind every dollar earned,

1113
01:20:04,273 --> 01:20:06,822
there was Andy, keeping the books.

1114
01:20:07,685 --> 01:20:11,188
Two deposits. Maine National
and New England First.

1115
01:20:11,189 --> 01:20:12,853
Night drops as always, sir.

1116
01:20:43,680 --> 01:20:45,014
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1117
01:20:45,515 --> 01:20:47,492
Two suits for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.

1118
01:20:47,493 --> 01:20:48,292
Yes, sir.

1119
01:20:48,393 --> 01:20:51,329
Tell them if they over-starch my shirts
again, they'll hear about it from me.

1120
01:20:51,330 --> 01:20:52,229
Yes, sir.

1121
01:20:52,230 --> 01:20:53,414
How do I look?

1122
01:20:54,315 --> 01:20:57,109
- Very nice, sir.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1123
01:20:57,110 --> 01:20:58,499
The Governor's going to be there.

1124
01:21:00,038 --> 01:21:01,364
Want the rest of this?

1125
01:21:02,665 --> 01:21:04,529
The woman can't bake worth shit.

1126
01:21:05,827 --> 01:21:07,199
Thank you, sir.

1127
01:21:09,989 --> 01:21:13,725
- He's got his fingers in a lot of pies, I hear.
- What you hear isn't half of it.

1128
01:21:13,726 --> 01:21:16,070
He's got scams you
haven't even dreamed of.

1129
01:21:16,171 --> 01:21:18,197
Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1130
01:21:18,298 --> 01:21:21,258
There's a river of dirty money
running through this place.

1131
01:21:21,259 --> 01:21:24,295
But the problem with having all that
money is you'll have to explain...

1132
01:21:24,296 --> 01:21:26,764
- where it came from.
- That's where I come in.

1133
01:21:27,465 --> 01:21:29,850
I channel it, filter it, funnel it.

1134
01:21:29,851 --> 01:21:32,577
Stocks, securities, tax-free municipals.

1135
01:21:33,278 --> 01:21:35,330
I send that money out into the real world.

1136
01:21:35,431 --> 01:21:38,942
- And when it comes back...
- Clean as a virgin's honey pot, huh?

1137
01:21:38,943 --> 01:21:39,735
Cleaner.

1138
01:21:40,236 --> 01:21:43,744
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1139
01:21:46,618 --> 01:21:50,621
If they ever catch on, though, he's gonna
wind up in here wearing a number himself.

1140
01:21:51,122 --> 01:21:54,158
Now, Red, I thought you had
a little more faith in me than that.

1141
01:21:54,159 --> 01:21:57,336
I know you're good, Andy,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1142
01:21:57,737 --> 01:22:01,923
Now, anybody gets curious,
the FBI, the IRS, whatever,

1143
01:22:02,424 --> 01:22:05,586
- it's gonna lead to somebody.
- Sure it is. But not to me.

1144
01:22:05,587 --> 01:22:07,368
And certainly not to the Warden.

1145
01:22:11,935 --> 01:22:13,150
All right. Who?

1146
01:22:13,211 --> 01:22:14,603
Randall Stevens.

1147
01:22:15,304 --> 01:22:16,151
Who?

1148
01:22:16,557 --> 01:22:21,652
The silent silent partner. He's the guilty one,
Your Honor. The man with the bank accounts.

1149
01:22:22,153 --> 01:22:24,104
That's where the filtering process starts.

1150
01:22:24,205 --> 01:22:26,858
If they trace anything,
it's just going to lead to him.

1151
01:22:27,659 --> 01:22:28,826
But who is he?

1152
01:22:29,127 --> 01:22:31,253
He's a phantom, an apparition.

1153
01:22:31,454 --> 01:22:33,497
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1154
01:22:34,398 --> 01:22:37,076
I conjured him... out of thin air.

1155
01:22:37,877 --> 01:22:40,892
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1156
01:22:43,641 --> 01:22:46,301
Andy, you can't just make a person up.

1157
01:22:46,302 --> 01:22:49,513
Sure you can, if you know how the
system works, where the cracks are.

1158
01:22:49,914 --> 01:22:52,600
It's amazing what you
can accomplish by mail.

1159
01:22:52,901 --> 01:22:58,230
Mr. Stevens has a birth certificate,
a driver's license, social security number.

1160
01:22:58,531 --> 01:22:59,423
You're shitting me?

1161
01:22:59,424 --> 01:23:01,366
If they ever trace any of those accounts,

1162
01:23:01,367 --> 01:23:04,028
they're going to wind up chasing
a figment of my imagination.

1163
01:23:04,529 --> 01:23:06,493
Well, I'll be damned.

1164
01:23:08,207 --> 01:23:09,733
Did I say you were good?

1165
01:23:10,334 --> 01:23:11,986
Shit, you're a Rembrandt!

1166
01:23:12,687 --> 01:23:14,213
You know, the funny thing is,

1167
01:23:14,414 --> 01:23:18,255
on the outside, I was an honest
man, straight as an arrow.

1168
01:23:19,219 --> 01:23:21,675
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1169
01:23:30,555 --> 01:23:31,990
Ever bother you?

1170
01:23:32,974 --> 01:23:36,376
I don't run the scams, Red,
I just process the profits.

1171
01:23:36,477 --> 01:23:38,103
Fine line maybe but...

1172
01:23:38,954 --> 01:23:41,298
I also built that library

1173
01:23:41,399 --> 01:23:44,309
and used it to help a dozen guys
get a high school diploma.

1174
01:23:44,410 --> 01:23:46,469
Why do you think the Warden lets me do it?

1175
01:23:46,970 --> 01:23:48,905
To keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1176
01:23:49,506 --> 01:23:50,916
Money instead of sheets.

1177
01:23:51,117 --> 01:23:53,710
Well, I work cheap. That's the trade-off.

1178
01:23:53,911 --> 01:23:55,876
<font color=#ff00ff>[Siren wails]</font>

1179
01:23:59,417 --> 01:24:01,506
