01:39:53,712 --> 01:39:56,038
They'll see the flames for miles.

1419
01:39:56,239 --> 01:39:58,821
We'll dance around it like wild Injuns.

1420
01:40:00,127 --> 01:40:01,628
You understand me?

1421
01:40:02,029 --> 01:40:03,693
Catching my drift?

1422
01:40:07,101 --> 01:40:09,065
Or am I being obtuse?

1423
01:40:20,522 --> 01:40:23,128
Give him another month to think about it.

1424
01:40:31,158 --> 01:40:33,122
<font color=#ff00ff>[Lock clicks]</font>

1425
01:41:10,038 --> 01:41:12,966
My wife used to say I'm a hard man to know.

1426
01:41:14,067 --> 01:41:15,731
Like a closed book.

1427
01:41:16,661 --> 01:41:18,897
Complained about it all the time.

1428
01:41:19,498 --> 01:41:21,062
She was beautiful.

1429
01:41:23,594 --> 01:41:25,158
God, I loved her.

1430
01:41:28,882 --> 01:41:31,097
I just didn't know how to show it, that's all.

1431
01:41:33,720 --> 01:41:35,285
I killed her, Red.

1432
01:41:37,265 --> 01:41:39,230
I didn't pull the trigger.

1433
01:41:40,569 --> 01:41:42,433
But I drove her away.

1434
01:41:43,864 --> 01:41:46,190
That's why she died, because of me.

1435
01:41:46,691 --> 01:41:48,256
The way I am.

1436
01:41:57,119 --> 01:41:59,083
That don't make you a murderer.

1437
01:42:02,416 --> 01:42:04,380
A bad husband, maybe.

1438
01:42:07,879 --> 01:42:11,040
Feel bad about it if you want to,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1439
01:42:11,041 --> 01:42:12,142
No, I didn't.

1440
01:42:12,843 --> 01:42:14,365
Somebody else did.

1441
01:42:16,179 --> 01:42:18,144
And I wound up in here.

1442
01:42:20,642 --> 01:42:22,406
Bad luck, I guess.

1443
01:42:25,647 --> 01:42:26,540
Yeah.

1444
01:42:27,441 --> 01:42:28,917
It floats around.

1445
01:42:29,818 --> 01:42:31,961
It's got to land on somebody.

1446
01:42:32,962 --> 01:42:34,693
It was my turn, that's all.

1447
01:42:35,699 --> 01:42:38,039
I was in the path of the tornado.

1448
01:42:44,549 --> 01:42:48,082
I just didn't expect the storm
would last as long as it has.

1449
01:42:52,591 --> 01:42:54,388
Do you think you'll ever get out of here?

1450
01:42:55,560 --> 01:42:56,708
Me?

1451
01:42:59,523 --> 01:43:00,662
Yeah.

1452
01:43:02,025 --> 01:43:04,268
One day, when I've got a long, white beard

1453
01:43:04,269 --> 01:43:07,651
and two or three marbles rolling
around upstairs, they'll let me out.

1454
01:43:09,591 --> 01:43:11,255
I tell you where I'd go.

1455
01:43:12,686 --> 01:43:14,195
Zihuatanejo.

1456
01:43:15,196 --> 01:43:16,697
Zi... what?

1457
01:43:16,698 --> 01:43:18,324
Zihuatanejo.

1458
01:43:19,425 --> 01:43:21,290
It's in Mexico.

1459
01:43:22,604 --> 01:43:24,794
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1460
01:43:25,966 --> 01:43:28,226
You know what the Mexicans
say about the Pacific?

1461
01:43:28,627 --> 01:43:29,669
No.

1462
01:43:30,270 --> 01:43:32,534
They say it has no memory.

1463
01:43:34,716 --> 01:43:37,139
That's where I want to live the rest of my life.

1464
01:43:38,845 --> 01:43:41,210
A warm place with no memory.

1465
01:43:44,426 --> 01:43:46,399
Open up a little hotel,

1466
01:43:48,155 --> 01:43:49,814
right on the beach.

1467
01:43:50,315 --> 01:43:52,441
Buy some worthless old boat,

1468
01:43:52,742 --> 01:43:54,407
fix it up new.

1469
01:43:57,289 --> 01:43:58,781
Take my guests out.

1470
01:43:59,482 --> 01:44:00,746
Charter fishing.

1471
01:44:04,688 --> 01:44:06,694
Zihuatanejo, huh?

1472
01:44:09,843 --> 01:44:13,401
In a place like that, I could use a man
who knows how to get things.

1473
01:44:20,345 --> 01:44:22,935
I don't think I could make
it on the outside, Andy.

1474
01:44:29,813 --> 01:44:31,777
I've been in here most of my life.

1475
01:44:33,400 --> 01:44:35,276
I'm an institutional man now.

1476
01:44:35,777 --> 01:44:37,241
Just like Brooks was.

1477
01:44:38,780 --> 01:44:41,115
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1478
01:44:41,416 --> 01:44:42,880
I don't think so.

1479
01:44:45,629 --> 01:44:50,624
I mean... in here, I'm the guy who
can get things for you, sure, but...

1480
01:44:51,625 --> 01:44:56,427
Outside, all you need is the Yellow Pages.
Hell, I wouldn't even know where to begin.

1481
01:44:58,633 --> 01:45:00,151
The Pacific Ocean?

1482
01:45:00,952 --> 01:45:02,178
Shit.

1483
01:45:02,279 --> 01:45:04,532
About scare me to death,
something that big.

1484
01:45:04,779 --> 01:45:05,732
Not me.

1485
01:45:07,033 --> 01:45:09,973
I didn't shoot my wife and
I didn't shoot her lover.

1486
01:45:11,813 --> 01:45:14,824
Whatever mistakes I've made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1487
01:45:15,925 --> 01:45:17,873
That hotel, that boat.

1488
01:45:19,279 --> 01:45:21,327
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1489
01:45:26,277 --> 01:45:28,838
I don't think you ought to be
doing this to yourself, Andy.

1490
01:45:28,939 --> 01:45:30,765
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1491
01:45:31,566 --> 01:45:34,109
I mean, Mexico is way the hell
down there and you're in here...

1492
01:45:34,110 --> 01:45:35,437
and that's the way it is.

1493
01:45:36,238 --> 01:45:38,844
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1494
01:45:40,417 --> 01:45:42,681
It's down there and I'm in here.

1495
01:45:45,313 --> 01:45:48,187
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice, really.

1496
01:45:50,944 --> 01:45:52,570
Get busy living

1497
01:45:53,671 --> 01:45:55,670
or get busy dying.

1498
01:45:59,786 --> 01:46:01,251
Andy.

1499
01:46:04,332 --> 01:46:05,497
Red.

1500
01:46:08,261 --> 01:46:10,562
If you ever get out of here, do me a favor.

1501
01:46:10,963 --> 01:46:11,981
Sure, Andy.

1502
01:46:12,782 --> 01:46:13,595
Anything.

1503
01:46:15,401 --> 01:46:18,341
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1504
01:46:19,764 --> 01:46:22,642
Well, just... There's a lot
of hayfields up there.

1505
01:46:22,642 --> 01:46:27,871
One in particular. It's got a long rock wall,
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1506
01:46:27,872 --> 01:46:30,563
It's like something out
of a Robert Frost poem.

1507
01:46:31,960 --> 01:46:34,250
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1508
01:46:35,680 --> 01:46:40,055
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1509
01:46:41,077 --> 01:46:43,042
I asked and she said yes.

1510
01:46:47,292 --> 01:46:48,918
Promise me, Red,

1511
01:46:49,719 --> 01:46:53,227
if you ever get out, find that spot.

1512
01:46:54,591 --> 01:46:59,437
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that
has no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1513
01:46:59,738 --> 01:47:03,220
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1514
01:47:06,210 --> 01:47:09,187
There's something buried
under it, I want you to have.

1515
01:47:09,288 --> 01:47:10,773
What, Andy?

1516
01:47:11,274 --> 01:47:12,638
What's buried under there?

1517
01:47:14,653 --> 01:47:17,910
You'll have to pry it up... to see.

1518
01:47:23,670 --> 01:47:25,534
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1519
01:47:26,598 --> 01:47:28,065
He's talking funnier.

1520
01:47:29,167 --> 01:47:32,727
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1521
01:47:32,728 --> 01:47:36,253
That's fine during the day, but
at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1522
01:47:37,459 --> 01:47:39,001
Oh, Lord.

1523
01:47:40,002 --> 01:47:40,924
What?

1524
01:47:42,514 --> 01:47:44,932
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1525
01:47:45,133 --> 01:47:48,619
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1526
01:47:48,620 --> 01:47:52,481
- Six feet long.
- And you gave it to him?

1527
01:47:52,882 --> 01:47:56,643
- Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?
- Jesus, Heywood.

1528
01:47:56,644 --> 01:47:58,979
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1529
01:47:59,280 --> 01:48:00,981
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1530
01:48:00,982 --> 01:48:01,904
No.

1531
01:48:02,867 --> 01:48:04,577
Andy would never do that.

1532
01:48:05,278 --> 01:48:06,542
Never.

1533
01:48:08,406 --> 01:48:09,871
I don't know.

1534
01:48:12,335 --> 01:48:14,500
Every man has his breaking point.

1535
01:48:17,248 --> 01:48:19,282
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1536
01:48:19,283 --> 01:48:21,340
Just about finished, sir.

1537
01:48:37,997 --> 01:48:39,925
Three deposits tonight.

1538
01:48:47,829 --> 01:48:49,713
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1539
01:48:50,114 --> 01:48:53,659
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1540
01:48:54,060 --> 01:48:55,015
Yes, sir.

1541
01:49:00,333 --> 01:49:02,084
It's good having you back, Andy.

1542
01:49:02,585 --> 01:49:04,717
The place wasn't the same without you.

1543
01:49:06,965 --> 01:49:08,929
<font color=#ff00ff>[Whistles]</font>

1544
01:49:51,485 --> 01:49:54,516
<font color=#FF551>- GUARD:</font> Lights out!
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Click of light switches]</font>

1545
01:49:58,933 --> 01:50:00,898
<font color=#ff00ff>[Footsteps]</font>

1546
01:50:06,900 --> 01:50:08,864
<font color=#ff00ff>[Outer door closes]</font>

1547
01:50:25,376 --> 01:50:27,849
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I've had some long nights in stir.

1548
01:50:28,613 --> 01:50:31,306
Alone in the dark with
nothing but your thoughts,

1549
01:50:31,407 --> 01:50:33,742
time can draw out like a blade.

1550
01:50:33,743 --> 01:50:35,307
<font color=#ff00ff>[Thunder rumbles]</font>

1551
01:50:39,424 --> 01:50:42,339
That was the longest night of my life.

1552
01:50:52,278 --> 01:50:54,493
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gate buzzer]</font>

1553
01:50:58,201 --> 01:50:59,306
<font color=#FF551>GUARD:</font> Give me a count.

1554
01:51:04,165 --> 01:51:06,291
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1555
01:51:06,292 --> 01:51:08,309
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1556
01:51:08,410 --> 01:51:12,780
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2. Cell 245.

1557
01:51:12,981 --> 01:51:14,549
Dufresne.

1558
01:51:14,950 --> 01:51:17,349
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1559
01:51:20,173 --> 01:51:23,897
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1560
01:51:31,409 --> 01:51:35,070
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1561
01:51:35,071 --> 01:51:38,240
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1562
01:51:38,741 --> 01:51:39,955
You hear me?

1563
01:51:46,582 --> 01:51:48,547
Oh, my holy God.

1564
01:52:00,763 --> 01:52:02,728
<font color=#ff00ff>[Siren wails]</font>

1565
01:52:05,518 --> 01:52:07,628
I want every man on
this cell block questioned.

1566
01:52:08,229 --> 01:52:10,522
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1567
01:52:10,923 --> 01:52:12,012
Him!

1568
01:52:13,451 --> 01:52:15,116
Open 237.

1569
01:52:18,440 --> 01:52:20,949
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1570
01:52:21,250 --> 01:52:22,976
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1571
01:52:23,027 --> 01:52:24,711
Don't say that to me again.

1572
01:52:24,712 --> 01:52:27,431
- But, sir, he wasn't.
- I can see that, Haig!

1573
01:52:27,832 --> 01:52:29,025
You think I'm blind?

1574
01:52:30,126 --> 01:52:33,236
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1575
01:52:33,237 --> 01:52:33,937
No, sir.

1576
01:52:35,422 --> 01:52:36,548
What about you?

1577
01:52:36,549 --> 01:52:37,667
Are you blind?

1578
01:52:38,468 --> 01:52:40,594
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1579
01:52:41,095 --> 01:52:44,473
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1580
01:52:44,474 --> 01:52:45,829
Dufresne.

1581
01:52:47,602 --> 01:52:49,752
He was in his cell at lights out.

1582
01:52:49,953 --> 01:52:52,644
It stands to reason he'd
still be here in the morning.

1583
01:52:53,649 --> 01:52:55,209
I want him found.

1584
01:52:55,610 --> 01:52:59,279
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1585
01:52:59,322 --> 01:53:00,302
Yes, sir!

1586
01:53:01,949 --> 01:53:04,414
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1587
01:53:07,371 --> 01:53:08,293
Stand.

1588
01:53:09,540 --> 01:53:10,671
Well?

1589
01:53:14,170 --> 01:53:15,378
Well, what?

1590
01:53:15,379 --> 01:53:18,720
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1591
01:53:19,884 --> 01:53:21,893
He must have said something.

1592
01:53:21,994 --> 01:53:23,520
No, sir, Warden.

1593
01:53:23,821 --> 01:53:25,260
Not a word.

1594
01:53:26,883 --> 01:53:29,364
Lord, it's a miracle!

1595
01:53:30,028 --> 01:53:32,871
A man up and vanished
like a fart in the wind.

1596
01:53:33,172 --> 01:53:34,806
Nothing left but...

1597
01:53:35,207 --> 01:53:37,709
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1598
01:53:38,010 --> 01:53:41,154
And that cupcake on
the wall. Let's ask her.

1599
01:53:41,155 --> 01:53:45,697
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1600
01:53:46,202 --> 01:53:48,529
Ah... I guess not.

1601
01:53:48,930 --> 01:53:51,090
Why should she be any different?

1602
01:53:52,491 --> 01:53:54,334
This is a conspiracy.

1603
01:53:54,735 --> 01:53:56,228
That's what this is.

1604
01:53:56,829 --> 01:53:58,955
One... big...

1605
01:53:59,356 --> 01:54:01,091
damn conspiracy!

1606
01:54:01,092 --> 01:54:02,844
And everyone's in on it!

1607
01:54:03,545 --> 01:54:05,417
Including her!

1608
01:54:06,472 --> 01:54:08,020
<font color=#ff00ff>[Clattering]</font>

1609
01:54:31,914 --> 01:54:33,503
<font color=#ff00ff>[Sirens blare]</font>

1610
01:54:39,797 --> 01:54:41,756
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> In 1966,

1611
01:54:41,757 --> 01:54:45,775
Andy Dufresne escaped
from Shawshank Prison.

1612
01:54:48,164 --> 01:54:51,499
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1613
01:54:51,500 --> 01:54:53,226
a bar of soap

1614
01:54:53,227 --> 01:54:57,486
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1615
01:55:01,886 --> 01:55:06,807
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1616
01:55:07,108 --> 01:55:09,998
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1617
01:55:28,179 --> 01:55:30,143
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1618
01:55:31,307 --> 01:55:34,193
I imagine it appealed to
his meticulous nature.

1619
01:55:34,894 --> 01:55:36,670
An Ice Age here,

1620
01:55:37,171 --> 01:55:39,336
a million years of mountain-building there.

1621
01:55:40,700 --> 01:55:43,598
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1622
01:55:44,328 --> 01:55:46,255
That's all it takes, really.

1623
01:55:47,156 --> 01:55:48,282
Pressure...

1624
01:55:48,683 --> 01:55:50,242
and time.

1625
01:55:51,243 --> 01:55:53,959
That and a big goddamn poster.

1626
01:55:55,164 --> 01:55:56,790
<font color=#ff00ff>[Coughing]</font>

1627
01:55:57,291 --> 01:55:58,667
Like I said,

1628
01:55:58,968 --> 01:56:02,642
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1629
01:56:05,558 --> 01:56:10,712
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby was
toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1630
01:56:10,813 --> 01:56:12,877
A handful at a time.

1631
01:56:14,333 --> 01:56:16,385
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1632
01:56:16,686 --> 01:56:19,704
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1633
01:56:19,705 --> 01:56:22,095
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1634
01:56:23,009 --> 01:56:25,073
I'm just about finished, sir.

1635
01:56:46,390 --> 01:56:48,355
Three deposits tonight.

1636
01:56:55,850 --> 01:56:57,772
Andy did like he was told.

1637
01:56:58,436 --> 01:57:01,619
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1638
01:57:05,527 --> 01:57:07,453
The guard simply didn't notice.

1639
01:57:08,054 --> 01:57:09,280
Neither did I.

1640
01:57:09,781 --> 01:57:14,497
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1641
01:57:49,320 --> 01:57:51,284
<font color=#ff00ff>[Thunderclap]</font>

1642
01:59:18,159 --> 01:59:24,414
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1643
01:59:24,915 --> 01:59:25,665
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gags]</font>

1644
01:59:25,967 --> 01:59:28,251
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1645
01:59:28,252 --> 01:59:30,216
<font color=#ff00ff>[Coughs and spits]</font>

1646
01:59:32,482 --> 01:59:34,971
500 yards.

1647
01:59:35,435 --> 01:59:38,516
That's the length of five football fields.

1648
01:59:39,080 --> 01:59:41,811
Just shy of half a mile.

1649
02:00:23,474 --> 02:00:25,063
<font color=#ff00ff>[Laughs]</font>

1650
02:00:36,954 --> 02:00:41,783
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1651
02:00:42,184 --> 02:00:44,786
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1652
02:00:44,987 --> 02:00:47,589
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1653
02:00:47,990 --> 02:00:49,516
Until that moment,

1654
02:00:49,717 --> 02:00:51,376
he didn't exist,

1655
02:00:51,677 --> 02:00:54,520
- except on paper.
- May I help you?

1656
02:00:54,521 --> 02:00:56,548
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> He had all the proper ID,

1657
02:00:56,649 --> 02:01:00,460
driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.

1658
02:01:00,661 --> 02:01:03,638
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1659
02:01:03,689 --> 02:01:07,066
I must say, I'm sorry to
be losing your business.

1660
02:01:07,067 --> 02:01:08,951
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1661
02:01:09,152 --> 02:01:10,628
Thank you.

1662
02:01:11,029 --> 02:01:12,805
I'm sure I will.

1663
02:01:13,106 --> 02:01:14,916
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1664
02:01:15,017 --> 02:01:16,443
Will there be anything else?

1665
02:01:16,844 --> 02:01:17,644
Please...

1666
02:01:18,228 --> 02:01:20,497
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1667
02:01:21,098 --> 02:01:22,791
I'd be happy to.

1668
02:01:24,292 --> 02:01:26,110
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1669
02:01:26,711 --> 02:01:30,887
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen
banks in the Portland area that morning.

1670
02:01:31,675 --> 02:01:38,323
All told, he blew town with better than
$370,000 of Warden Norton's money.

1671
02:01:38,724 --> 02:01:42,732
- Severance pay for 19 years.
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Phone rings]</font>

1672
02:01:48,818 --> 02:01:51,491
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1673
02:01:58,786 --> 02:02:00,750
<font color=#ff00ff>[Sirens wail]</font>

1674
02:02:30,067 --> 02:02:31,990
<font color=#ff00ff>[Sirens approaching]</font>

1675
02:02:43,831 --> 02:02:47,016
Byron Hadley? You have
the right to remain silent.

1676
02:02:47,017 --> 02:02:48,643
If you give up the right to remain silent,...

1677
02:02:48,644 --> 02:02:52,029
...anything you say will be held
against you in court of law.

1678
02:02:52,130 --> 02:02:53,590
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I wasn't there to see it.

1679
02:02:53,591 --> 02:02:57,850
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1680
02:03:04,093 --> 02:03:07,366
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1681
02:03:23,461 --> 02:03:24,694
Samuel Norton?

1682
02:03:24,795 --> 02:03:27,637
- We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.
<font color=#ff00ff>- [Banging on door]</font>

1683
02:03:30,936 --> 02:03:31,544
Norton!

1684
02:03:32,045 --> 02:03:32,696
Open the door.

1685
02:03:33,297 --> 02:03:35,228
I'm not sure which key it is.

1686
02:03:37,927 --> 02:03:38,874
Norton!

1687
02:03:44,959 --> 02:03:46,623
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1688
02:03:58,747 --> 02:04:02,016
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> I like to think the last
thing that went through his head,

1689
02:04:02,317 --> 02:04:03,910
other than that bullet,

1690
02:04:04,111 --> 02:04:08,394
was to wonder how the hell Andy
Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1691
02:04:09,583 --> 02:04:11,150
Carter, James...

1692
02:04:11,151 --> 02:04:14,512
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1693
02:04:14,813 --> 02:04:16,744
I got a postcard in the mail.

1694
02:04:17,975 --> 02:04:21,177
It was blank, but the postmark said...

1695
02:04:21,178 --> 02:04:23,313
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1696
02:04:23,914 --> 02:04:25,140
Fort Hancock.

1697
02:04:25,641 --> 02:04:27,267
Right on the border.

1698
02:04:27,768 --> 02:04:29,594
That's where Andy crossed.

1699
02:04:30,095 --> 02:04:34,153
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1700
02:04:34,717 --> 02:04:37,181
it always makes me laugh.

1701
02:04:38,920 --> 02:04:40,546
Andy Dufresne,

1702
02:04:40,947 --> 02:04:45,173
who crawled through a river of shit
and came out clean on the other side.

1703
02:04:46,203 --> 02:04:47,829
Andy Dufresne,

1704
02:04:48,330 --> 02:04:49,928
headed for the Pacific.

1705
02:04:52,835 --> 02:04:55,361
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1706
02:04:55,462 --> 02:04:59,257
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1707
02:04:59,258 --> 02:05:02,110
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1708
02:05:02,911 --> 02:05:04,846
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1709
02:05:04,847 --> 02:05:07,432
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1710
02:05:07,433 --> 02:05:09,397
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1711
02:05:10,986 --> 02:05:13,446
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1712
02:05:13,647 --> 02:05:15,373
Andy being gone.

1713
02:05:15,674 --> 02:05:19,357
I have to remind myself that some
birds aren't meant to be caged.

1714
02:05:20,562 --> 02:05:22,327
Their feathers are just too bright.

1715
02:05:24,091 --> 02:05:26,217
And when they fly away,

1716
02:05:26,318 --> 02:05:30,618
the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1717
02:05:31,790 --> 02:05:33,233
But still...

1718
02:05:33,434 --> 02:05:37,583
the place you live in is that much more
drab and empty that they're gone.

1719
02:05:42,051 --> 02:05:44,482
I guess I just miss my friend.

1720
02:06:09,085 --> 02:06:10,441
Please sit down.

1721
02:06:15,951 --> 02:06:17,560
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1722
02:06:17,961 --> 02:06:21,422
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1723
02:06:22,023 --> 02:06:23,980
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1724
02:06:26,228 --> 02:06:27,492
Rehabilitated?

1725
02:06:29,756 --> 02:06:31,521
Well, now, let me see.

1726
02:06:32,685 --> 02:06:35,299
You know, I don't have
any idea what that means.

1727
02:06:37,214 --> 02:06:39,840
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1728
02:06:39,841 --> 02:06:42,364
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1729
02:06:44,363 --> 02:06:46,527
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1730
02:06:47,691 --> 02:06:49,926
A politician's word so that...

1731
02:06:50,627 --> 02:06:55,711
young fellas like yourself can wear
a suit and a tie and... have a job.

1732
02:06:58,151 --> 02:06:59,916
What do you really want to know?

1733
02:07:01,004 --> 02:07:03,005
Am I sorry for what I did?

1734
02:07:03,406 --> 02:07:04,596
Well, are you?

1735
02:07:06,443 --> 02:07:09,308
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1736
02:07:10,514 --> 02:07:14,221
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1737
02:07:17,438 --> 02:07:20,402
I look back on the way I was then.

1738
02:07:22,109 --> 02:07:23,735
A young...

1739
02:07:24,536 --> 02:07:27,601
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1740
02:07:31,060 --> 02:07:32,724
I wanna talk to him.

1741
02:07:34,621 --> 02:07:37,169
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1742
02:07:37,833 --> 02:07:39,797
tell him the way things are.

1743
02:07:41,987 --> 02:07:43,252
But I can't.

1744
02:07:45,482 --> 02:07:47,347
That kid's long gone.

1745
02:07:48,761 --> 02:07:51,125
This old man is all that's left.

1746
02:07:52,773 --> 02:07:54,554
I gotta live with that.

1747
02:07:55,809 --> 02:07:59,771
Rehabilitated? It's just a bullshit word.

1748
02:08:00,672 --> 02:08:05,573
So you go on and stamp your form,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1749
02:08:06,679 --> 02:08:08,505
Because to tell you the truth,

1750
02:08:09,106 --> 02:08:11,087
I don't give a shit.

1751
02:08:49,530 --> 02:08:51,494
<font color=#ff00ff>[Gate closes]</font>

1752
02:09:11,009 --> 02:09:12,974
<font color=#ff00ff>[Siren passes outside]</font>

1753
02:09:37,559 --> 02:09:39,084
Here you go, miss.

1754
02:09:41,907 --> 02:09:43,545
Rest room break, boss?

1755
02:09:49,214 --> 02:09:53,689
You don't need to ask me every time you
need to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1756
02:09:54,720 --> 02:09:55,867
Yes, sir.

1757
02:10:06,440 --> 02:10:09,363
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> 40 years I've been
asking permission to piss.

1758
02:10:10,485 --> 02:10:13,375
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1759
02:10:17,225 --> 02:10:19,090
There's a harsh truth to face.

1760
02:10:20,871 --> 02:10:23,385
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1761
02:10:31,723 --> 02:10:35,464
All I do any more is think
of ways to break my parole...

1762
02:10:36,228 --> 02:10:38,492
...so maybe they'd send me back.

1763
02:10:43,818 --> 02:10:46,283
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1764
02:10:47,080 --> 02:10:50,938
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1765
02:10:52,527 --> 02:10:55,801
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1766
02:10:56,365 --> 02:10:59,246
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1767
02:11:01,245 --> 02:11:03,409
Only one thing stops me.

1768
02:11:04,773 --> 02:11:07,038
A promise I made to Andy.

1769
02:11:27,688 --> 02:11:28,952
Here it is.

1770
02:11:39,574 --> 02:11:41,239
Much obliged, sir.

1771
02:15:04,905 --> 02:15:06,869
<font color=#ff00ff>[Bird calls]</font>

1772
02:15:20,462 --> 02:15:21,837
<font color=#FF551>ANDY:</font> Dear Red,

1773
02:15:21,838 --> 02:15:24,381
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1774
02:15:24,582 --> 02:15:28,519
And if you've come this far, maybe
you're willing to come a little further.

1775
02:15:29,020 --> 02:15:31,485
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1776
02:15:33,600 --> 02:15:35,564
Zihuatanejo.

1777
02:15:36,828 --> 02:15:40,147
I could use a good man to help
me get my project on wheels.

1778
02:15:40,948 --> 02:15:44,581
I'll keep an eye out for you
and the chessboard ready.

1779
02:15:45,445 --> 02:15:46,604
Remember, Red,

1780
02:15:46,905 --> 02:15:49,431
hope is a good thing.

1781
02:15:49,532 --> 02:15:51,358
Maybe the best of things.

1782
02:15:51,559 --> 02:15:53,624
And no good thing ever dies.

1783
02:15:54,287 --> 02:15:57,230
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1784
02:15:57,331 --> 02:15:58,958
and finds you well.

1785
02:15:59,459 --> 02:16:01,840
Your friend, Andy.

1786
02:16:36,037 --> 02:16:39,795
<font color=#FF551>RED:</font> Get busy living or get busy dying.

1787
02:16:42,419 --> 02:16:44,383
That's goddamn right.

1788
02:16:50,010 --> 02:16:52,219
For the second time in my life,

1789
02:16:52,220 --> 02:16:54,585
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1790
02:16:55,974 --> 02:16:58,058
Parole violation.

1791
02:16:58,559 --> 02:17:02,250
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1792
02:17:03,123 --> 02:17:05,149
Not for an old crook like me.

1793
02:17:05,350 --> 02:17:07,414
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1794
02:17:10,947 --> 02:17:15,655
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit
still or hold a thought in my head.

1795
02:17:16,119 --> 02:17:19,204
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1796
02:17:19,685 --> 02:17:24,798
A free man at the start of a long journey
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1797
02:17:27,797 --> 02:17:30,445
I hope I can make it across the border.

1798
02:17:31,943 --> 02:17:35,016
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1799
02:17:37,015 --> 02:17:40,805
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1800
02:17:42,879 --> 02:17:44,335
I hope.